title: CEVSOC Presents: Into The Blueprint
description:
Friend: So what’re you studying?

You: Civil/Environmental Engineering

Friend: So what kind of stuff does that involve?

You: Soil, concrete, water, trains

Friend: Is that really all there is to your degree? Is that really all there is to you? Who are you? 

You: 👁👄👁

We often forget about the interplay of what defines us and what we do for work or study, especially in the field of engineering where everything is so physically based. But in reality, recognising what defines us in terms of our gender, race, ethnicity, sexual orientation, socio-economic status, age, physical abilities and our religious beliefs makes us perform better as an individual or in our community of school or work. 

In CEVSOC’s podcast, we will be chatting to your peers and people from the industry to share their stories and perspectives on topics relating to Diversity and Inclusion. 

You can listen to our podcast on Spotify or interact with us while we are discussing the topics on Facebook Live and Instagram Live. 

WHEN: First release on Wednesday March 10th (Week 4) 
TIME: 12:00PM-12:45PM 
WHERE: Online via Facebook, Instagram, Spotify (links coming soon!)

------------------------ ABOUT US ------------------------
CEVSOC is the student society for the UNSW School of Civil and Environmental Engineering, the top ranked Civil Engineering School in Australia. We are the largest student-run school society under the UNSW Faculty of Engineering, running social, academic and professional development events for approximately 1500 students. COVID can't keep a good play down! 

This production unfortunately had to be cancelled a few weeks out from show-week last year due to the onset of the pandemic, but we're very excited to announce it's return! 


Synopsis:
On his 30th birthday, investment banker Joseph K is ‘arrested’ for seemingly no reason and without any immediately visible consequences. As K grapples with the subtle and strange ways this event impacts his life, he struggles to deal with pressure from his co-workers, concern from his family and an infuriating yet hilarious unhelpfulness from anyone he turns to for help. When his case eventually consumes his whole life, K succumbs to paranoia and burns all his bridges in a climactic, surreal confrontation.

A retelling of Franz Kafka’s classic novel "The Trial" set in modern-day London, this play deals with themes of bureaucracy, surveillance and individual freedoms through increasingly dark comedy and satire.
